Fog water has turned into an alternative and sustainable source of fresh water, especially in dry regions that experience frequent fog events. With rapidly changing climate, overconsumption, inadequate management, among other forces, has led to the scarcity of water around the globe and specifically in arid regions is more pronounced now. This scarcity directly impacts the availability of drinking water, agricultural production, and food availability. Regions like these greatly benefit from harvesting fog water. Coastal areas of Angola, Namibia and South Africa, Kenya, Eastern Yemen, Oman, China, Sri Lanka, Mexico, along with the mountainous regions of Peru, Chile, and Ecuador, are some of the potential sites that can benefit from the installation of fog water harvesting systems (Climate Technology Centre & Network). Southeast Asia also sees fog water as a promising water source to deal with the water scarcity in regions prone to fog events in the near future (Ismail and Go 2021). Harvesting fog water requires no ongoing energy supply making it ideal for isolated and rural communities, where water usage is relatively low (Domen et al. 2014). Fog water can also be seen as both complementary and supplementary to the existing water resource. Apart from being a green technology, providing water and ecosystem service, fog water harvesting projects have also impacted the economic aspect by providing livelihood and social aspects by promoting gender equality in the regions they are running (Qadir et al. 2018). Fog water is collected with the help of mesh nets standing perpendicular to the direction of fog-carrying winds. When the fog droplets come in contact with the net, they get trapped; as the droplet size increases by coalescence, it becomes heavier and drops down into a receptacle, from where it is collected in tanks. In theory, collecting fog water is simple, but the attempt is futile if the actual feasible potential of the fog water collection rate is not predicted. So, at present, there are two models for depicting the potential of fog water collection in any given area using the mesh collector: Impaction model, fog is collected in the mesh by impaction, direct interception and Brownian diffusion of fog droplets even so the contribution by the latter two is almost negligible as the interception only happens for droplets that come within the range of one droplet radius from the mesh and Brownian diffusion is only possible for droplets with diameter > 0.1 μm. So, considering impactions the main process fog water collection can be determined by the following formula (Ritter et al. 2008):q=3.6wAηV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
